title: Big Ten East Division Power Rankings: With Michigan On The Rise, They#039;re Set to Host Michigan State
text:
Get Sports Alerts 
14 Oct 2015 04:33 PM EST 
-by Daniel Mogollon, Staff Writer; Image: Michigan wide receiver Jehu Chesson versus Northwestern. (Image Source: Leon Halip/Getty Images) 
Big Ten East division power rankings following Week 6: 
(1) Ohio State Buckeyes (2); Record: 6-0 (2-0) 
Last Week: Won vs. Maryland 49-28 
Are they playing like the best team in the country, conference or division? No, but the Buckeyes have the most talent in the B1G, hands down. What we liked on Saturday? WR Braxton Miller was a factor with five catches for 79 yards and a TD and QB J.T. Barrett was efficient (12 carries, 62 yards; 2 of 26 passing, 26 yards) and very effective in the red zone (3 TDs). But I didn’t like 28 points allowed to a Maryland team that combined for six points against West Virginia and Michigan. 
Coming Up: 10/17: vs. Penn State; 10/24: @ Rutgers 
(2) Michigan Wolverines (3); Record: 5-1 (2-0) 
Last Week: Won vs. Northwestern 38-0 
It was the defensive battle everyone expected…at least when Northwestern had the ball as the Wolverines did not allowed a point for the third game in a row. The last time any FBS team had three-straight shutouts was 1995, the last time a Big Ten team did it was 1980. WR Jehu Chesson got the party started with an opening kickoff TD and QB Jake Rudock was a proficient 17 of 23 (season-high 73.9 %). 
Coming Up: 10/17: vs. Michigan State; 10/24: @ Minnesota 
(3) Michigan State Spartans; Record (1): 6-0 (2-0) 
Last Week: Won @ Rutgers 31-24 
The Spartans have simply tested fate one too many times for my liking. The offense isn’t as explosive as we hoped and the defense isn’t as dominant as it once was. Right now they’re not even the best team in their own state, never mind the B1G East. MSU doesn’t have that edge anymore…maybe taking on the underdog role against Michigan will help them rediscover it. 
Coming Up: 10/17: @ Michigan; 10/14: vs. Indiana 
(4) Penn State Nittany Lions (4); Record: 5-1 (2-0) 
Last Week: Won vs. Indiana 29-7 
The passing game still isn’t very crisp, completing 53.8 percent of your passes isn’t impressive, but they are getting more efficient. QB Christian Hackenberg threw two TDs, ran for two TD, and now has six scoring strikes with no INTs in his past three games. Former walk-on, DE Carl Nassib , had another monster game with two sacks and two forced fumbles. They’re clearly behind the top three and clearly ahead of the bottom three in the B1GE. 
Coming Up: 10/17: @ Ohio State; 10/24: vs. Maryland 
(5) Rutgers Scarlet Knights (6); Record: 2-3 (0-2) 
Last Week: Lost vs. Michigan State 31-24 
You don’t think WR Leonte Carroo is a difference maker? In his return the senior caught seven passes for 134 yards, including all three of RU’s touchdowns against the Spartans. They were expected to have a strong running game and his presence makes them a much more balanced offense. 
Coming Up: 10/17: @ Indiana; 10/24: vs. Ohio State 
(6) Indiana Hoosiers (5); Record: 4-2 (0-2) 
Last Week: Lost vs. Penn State 29-7 
The Hoosiers lose a second-straight game and continue to lose quarterbacks as Zander Diamont was knocked out by Penn State and third-stringer Danny Cameron (6 of 16, INT) struggled off the bench. Sound familiar? Whether it’s a reason or an excuse the inability to stay healthy at the QB position may once again derail what once looked like a promising season (we’re talking 6 or 7 wins) in Bloomington. If they can’t turn things around this week, expect the losing streak to reach six games, at least. 
Coming Up: 10/17: vs. Rutgers; 10/24: @ Michigan State 
(7) Maryland Terrapins (7); Record: 2-4 (0-2) 
Last Week: Lost @ Ohio State 49-28 
As it’s painfully obvious that the Terps are the worst team in the division, maybe the conference, it’s not the biggest surprise that HC Randy Edsall would be fired, although maybe not in-season. It was their fourth loss of the year by at least 21 points, including their third straight. I’m not saying Edsall didn’t deserve to be canned, but their QB issues will remain. Sure, Perry Hills ran for 170 yards and two TDs against OSU but was 10 of 27 passing (37 percent) with two INTs (1 TD). 
Coming Up: 10/17: Idle; 10/24: vs. Penn State 
Daniel Mogollon is a member of the Pro Football Writers of America and the Football Writers Association of America. He is also a voter for the Thorpe and the Rotary Lombardi Award, as well as the Latino Sports MVP Awards. You can reach him via email: danmogollon@gmail.com .
